		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Neither GIMP nor Photoshop were designed for pixelart but for editing of way more complex images, so it's no wonder that doing pixelart with them is much harder than one feels it should be.</div><br />I find GIMP is quite good for pixel art, and use it frequently for this. I found this tutorial helpful: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PONe4IIYSnQp" class="postlink">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PONe4IIYSnQp</a><br /><br />The only ways I find it lacking are that palettes are not very convenient (though they can still be done), and it's not very good at all for animation.<br /><br />For animated pixel art I use Aseprite, which I think is not as good an image editor as GIMP but is quite good for animation.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
